          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>Which mnemonic correctly represents the five levels of the brachial plexus in or</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>Which mnemonic correctly represents the five levels of the brachial plexus in order from proximal to distal?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Roots, Trunks, Cords, Divisions, Branches</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>This reverses the order of divisions and cords. Divisions come before cords — the trunks split into divisions, which then regroup into cords.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Roots, Trunks, Divisions, Cords, Branches</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct. Robert Taylor Drinks Cold Beer — Roots, Trunks, Divisions, Cords, Branches. The cords are named for their position around the axillary artery: lateral, posterior, and medial.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Roots, Divisions, Trunks, Cords, Branches</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Divisions do not come before trunks. The five roots first merge into three trunks, and only then does each trunk split into anterior and posterior divisions.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Roots, Trunks, Divisions, Branches, Cords</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Branches are the final output of the plexus, not an intermediate stage. The cords must form before terminal branches emerge.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "The correct order is Roots, Trunks, Divisions, Cords, Branches — remembered as Robert Taylor Drinks Cold Beer. Getting this sequence right is essential for localising brachial plexus injuries."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Excellent. Roots → Trunks → Divisions → Cords → Branches. Each level reorganises the nerve fibres so that functionally related fibres end up in the same terminal nerve."
                }
              ],
              "behaviour": {
