          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>A patient with Klumpke's paralysis of the right hand would most likely present with which finding?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Arm held in the waiter's tip position</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The waiter's tip position is characteristic of Erb's palsy (upper trunk, C5–C6), not Klumpke's paralysis. In Erb's palsy the shoulder and elbow are affected while the hand is spared.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Inability to abduct the arm beyond 15 degrees</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Loss of abduction suggests deltoid paralysis from axillary nerve injury, not Klumpke's paralysis. In Klumpke's, the shoulder is spared because the upper trunk is intact.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Claw hand with hyperextended metacarpophalangeal joints</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct. Klumpke's paralysis (C8–T1) destroys the intrinsic hand muscles. Without lumbricals and interossei, the long extensors are unopposed at the MCP joints, producing the claw deformity.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Wrist drop with inability to extend the fingers</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Wrist drop results from radial nerve injury, not lower trunk damage. The radial nerve primarily carries fibres from C5–C8 via the posterior cord.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "Klumpke's paralysis injures the lower trunk (C8–T1), paralysing the intrinsic muscles of the hand. This produces a claw hand — hyperextended MCP joints and flexed IP joints. Remember: Erb's spares the hand, Klumpke's spares the shoulder."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Well done. Klumpke's paralysis affects C8 and T1, paralysing intrinsic hand muscles and producing a claw hand. If T1 is involved, Horner's syndrome (ptosis, miosis, anhidrosis) may also appear due to disrupted sympathetic fibres."
                }
              ],
              "behaviour": {
