          "displayType": "poster",
          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>Which rotator cuff muscle initiates abduction of the arm and is most commonly to</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>Which rotator cuff muscle initiates abduction of the arm and is most commonly torn?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Infraspinatus</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Infraspinatus produces lateral rotation of the arm, not abduction. It lies below the spine of the scapula and shares the suprascapular nerve supply with supraspinatus.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Subscapularis</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Subscapularis is the only rotator cuff muscle that produces medial rotation. It occupies the anterior surface of the scapula and does not contribute to abduction.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Teres minor</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Teres minor assists with lateral rotation alongside infraspinatus. It is supplied by the axillary nerve, not the suprascapular nerve, and is not the primary abductor.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Supraspinatus</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct. Supraspinatus initiates the first 0–15 degrees of abduction before the deltoid takes over. Its tendon passes under the acromion, making it vulnerable to impingement and the most frequently torn rotator cuff muscle.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "Supraspinatus initiates abduction (0–15°) and is the most commonly torn rotator cuff muscle. Use the mnemonic SITS to remember the four muscles and note that three produce lateral rotation while only subscapularis produces medial rotation."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Exactly right. Remember SITS: Supraspinatus (abduction initiation), Infraspinatus (lateral rotation), Teres minor (lateral rotation), Subscapularis (medial rotation). When supraspinatus tears, the patient cannot smoothly initiate abduction — producing the painful arc sign."
                }
              ],
              "behaviour": {
