          "label": "<p>A nurse asks you to mark the correct site for an intramuscular deltoid injection</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>A nurse asks you to mark the correct site for an intramuscular deltoid injection. Which landmark ensures the axillary nerve is not injured?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>The midpoint of the deltoid muscle belly</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The midpoint is too low. The axillary nerve wraps around the surgical neck of the humerus at approximately this level, placing it directly in the path of the needle.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Two to three finger-breadths below the acromion</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct. Injecting in the upper third of the deltoid, 2–3 finger-breadths below the acromion, keeps the needle safely above the axillary nerve, which runs at the level of the surgical neck of the humerus.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>At the deltoid tuberosity on the lateral humerus</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The deltoid tuberosity is in the lower third of the muscle, far too low. At this level, the needle would be near or beyond the axillary nerve's path around the surgical neck.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Just above the insertion of the deltoid</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The insertion of the deltoid is at the deltoid tuberosity, in the lower portion of the muscle. Injecting here places the needle dangerously close to the axillary nerve.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "The safe zone is the upper third of the deltoid, identified by measuring 2–3 finger-breadths below the acromion. The axillary nerve runs at the level of the surgical neck of the humerus, which lies in the lower deltoid. Injecting too low risks permanent nerve damage and loss of arm abduction."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Perfect. The axillary nerve curves around the surgical neck of the humerus in the lower deltoid region. Targeting 2–3 finger-breadths below the acromion keeps the injection in the upper third, well above the nerve. This is a preventable cause of deltoid paralysis."
                }
              ],
